nited Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1321–Abt 1376":"circa 1321–circa 1376","1321–1376":"1321–1376","1322–1365":"1322–1365","1284–Female":"1284–Overleden","1343–1408":"1343–1408","1352–Male":"1352–Overleden","1280–1346":"1280–1346","1352":"1352","1284":"1284","1280":"1280","1346":"1346","Abt 1321":"circa 1321","Abt 1365":"circa 1365","Abt 1376":"circa 1376","1322":"1322","1343":"1343","17 October 1346":"17 oktober 1346","1365":"1365","1376":"1376","1321":"1321","1342":"1342","Abt 1352":"circa 1352","1408":"1408","Gowrie, Perth, Scotland":"Gowrie, Perthshire, Schotland","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ruthven, Perth, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1321–Abt 1376":"about 1321–about 1376","1321–1376":"1321–1376","1322–1365":"1322–1365","1284–Female":"1284–Deceased","1343–1408":"1343–1408","1352–Male":"1352–Deceased","1280–1346":"1280–1346","1352":"1352","1284":"1284","1280":"1280","1346":"1346","Abt 1321":"about 1321","Abt 1365":"about 1365","Abt 1376":"about 1376","1322":"1322","1343":"1343","17 October 1346":"17 October 1346","1365":"1365","1376":"1376","1321":"1321","1342":"1342","Abt 1352":"about 1352","1408":"1408","Gowrie, Perth, Scotland":"Gowrie, Perthshire, Scotland","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ruthven, Perth, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ruthven","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name, traditionally pronounced ‘Ri-ven’, from Ruthven by Huntingtower (Perthshire); also possibly from Ruthven (Angus) and various other places of that name throughout Scotland, named either with Gaelic <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’ + <i>mhaighin</i> ‘place’ or with a cognate of Welsh <i>rhudd faen</i> ‘red stone’. The oldest family of this name, the lords of the barony of Ruthven by Perth, were descended from Thor, son of Swain, lord of Tranent in Lothian and first sheriff of Edinburgh on record in the mid 12th century. The family eventually gained the title of Earl of Gowrie, but because of what became known as ‘the Gowrie Conspiracy’ the title was forfeited and from 1600 to 1641 the surname itself was proscribed. The title was later restored to the family, and the present Earl of Gowrie bears the surname <i>Ruthven</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Ruthven Laird of Ruthven was born about 1321, in Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of William Ruthven Laird of Ruthven. He married Mrs. Johanna Ruthven in 1342, in Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1376, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 57."},"et":{"Abt 1321–Abt 1376":"umbes 1321–umbes 1376","1321–1376":"1321–1376","1322–1365":"1322–1365","1284–Female":"1284–Surnud","1343–1408":"1343–1408","1352–Male":"1352–Surnud","1280–1346":"1280–1346","1352":"1352","1284":"1284","1280":"1280",